{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493193"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1250"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1250"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.68,0.03,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1250"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92090"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"207"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41928"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is admitted to a General Medical Unit at 8 pm in the evening for IV antibiotics for community acquired pneumonia. He has a medical history of COPD, osteoarthritis and gout. His medications include allopurinol, paracetamol and a tiotropium/olodaterol inhaler. He smokes 25 cigarettes/day and drinks 5-6 standard drinks of alcohol a day on most days of the week. He denies intravenous drug use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn the morning ward round the next day, he reports he has developed nausea and anxiety, and that he slept poorly in hospital. He denies chest pain or cough and reports his shortness of breath has slightly improved. On examination, his pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 95% on 2L nasal oxygen, and temperature 38\u00b0C. He appears diaphoretic and a tremor is visible in both hands. There are crackles over the right lung base and a dull percussion note on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments would be most effective to treat his current symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous pyridoxine","Oral acamprosate","Oral diazepam","Intramuscular haloperidol","Intravenous thiamine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has features of moderate community acquired pneumonia as well as features of acute alcohol withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute alcohol withdrawal is characterised by the following constellation of symptoms; anxiety, tremor, sweating, nausea/vomiting, agitation, headache and perceptual disturbances. \u003Cstrong\u003EOral diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is the mainstay for treating acute alcohol withdrawal, as it reduces symptoms of acute alcohol withdrawal and also prevents the dangerous complications of seizures. Oral lorazepam is sometimes substituted if the patient has significant liver disease. This patient presents with symptoms of moderate alcohol withdrawal. Whilst mild withdrawal can be managed with supportive care, benzodiazepines are still typically used if mild to moderate withdrawal is predicted, because it can be difficult to predict severe withdrawal.  The effect of respiratory depression of the oral benzodiazepine is minimal and is outweighed by the effects of reducing withdrawal symptoms (especially compared to IV clonazepam or similar.)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient also requires \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous thiamine\u003C/strong\u003E, but IV thiamine will not treat his current symptoms. Instead, IV thiamine will reduce his risk of developing Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy. Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy is a complication of thiamine deficiency which is commonly associated with chronic alcohol abuse. It is characterised by ophthalmoplegia, ataxia and confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acamprosate\u003C/strong\u003E is not used in acute alcohol withdrawal, but is used to reduce cravings in alcohol-dependent patients trying to remain abstinent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular haloperidol \u003C/strong\u003Eis used for agitation and behavioural emergencies when oral options cannot be used, and has no place in treating an adherent patient experiencing mild acute alcohol withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous pyridoxine \u003C/strong\u003E(vitamin B6) deficiency is associated with anaemia, peripheral neuropathy, rash and depression, and is not related to alcohol withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral diazepam can provide effective symptomatic relief in cases of acute alcohol withdrawal."],"references":["Bayard M, McIntyre J, Hill KR et al. Alcohol withdrawal syndrome Am Fam Phys 2004; 69:1443-50.","Alcohol Withdrawal [Published June 2023]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {03/09/2024}. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92090"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1250"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92090"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T17:50:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T17:09:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1250"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109687"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{